The tension between the ANC and its suspended MP Mervyn Dirks is healthy in a multi-party democracy according to Deputy Speaker, Lechesa Tsenoli. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The situation between the ANC and its suspended MP Mervyn Dirks is a necessary tension. That’s the view of Parliament deputy speaker Lechesa Tsenoli. READ: Party slush funds | Scopa gives Ramaphosa 10-day deadline The ANC suspended Dirks over calls for President Cyril Ramaphosa to answer to allegations of the misappropriation of state funds. Scopa has given Ramaphosa up to ten 10 days to respond to its questions in writing. Tsenoli spoke to JJ Tabane on Power to Truth. READ: Scopa to request Ramaphosa's written submission over alleged comments on fund abuse "If the ANC in this instance is unhappy with the manner in which the member handled this matter, they are likely to get a reaction such as you are describing," he said. "My view is that it's a necessary tension that must continue to grow because this is a multi-party system... But internal party rules are likely to play a critical role for members to do it as robust as they can without consequences arising for them from doing that."